	<string># üé© Alfred Filenames Db

‚ú® *Grab instantly filenames and rename them with a Spreadsheet* ‚ú®

![workflow](./images/workflow.webp)

## ‚úÖ Prerequisite

* üçé MacOS.
* üé© Alfred 5. Note that the [Alfred Powerpack](https://www.alfredapp.com/powerpack/) is required to use workflows.
* üìä Any spreadsheet software which can open `.xlsx` files like [Microsoft Excel](https://apps.apple.com/fr/app/microsoft-excel/id462058435?mt=12), [Numbers](https://apps.apple.com/us/app/numbers/id409203825?mt=12), [WPSOffice](https://apps.apple.com/fr/app/wps-office-pdf-docs-sheets/id1468073139?mt=12), [LibreOffice](https://www.libreoffice.org/download/download-libreoffice/)...
* ‚ÄºÔ∏è Requires **python 3.6** or above.

## üßô‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è Invoke the Workflow

There is 2 flows in this workflow :

1. The first one allows you to grab filenames. It can be triggered by writing `getfilenames` keyword.
2. The second allows you to rename files based on the data in a selected spreadsheet. You can invoke this flow with the `renamefiles` keyword.

You can change these values by changing the `üïπÔ∏è Trigger 1` or `üïπÔ∏è Trigger 2` variables in workflow configuration panel [optionnal]. Please avoid putting the same trigger for the two flows.

## üß∞ Setup the workflow

### üë®‚Äçüíª Install dependencies

‚òëÔ∏è Install Python 3.6 or above. Check your version with :

`python --version`

### üìÇ Data (XLSX files and Logs) folder

‚ùó This variable cannot be empty. You can change it at your convenience in the workflow configuration panel.

It contains the xlsx files generated with the first flow + output logs of the the renaming operation generated by the second flow.

üí° Note that if you change the `Data folder` location after creating xlsx files and logs, you should probably move the files created along in the new folder.

![data_folder](./images/data_folder.webp)

## ü§ñ Usage of the workflow

### üìΩÔ∏è Register filenames in a Spreadsheet

Ensure that you select the right Level for the parameter `üîç Depth of the search`. If you want to include files in subdirectories increase the depth level.

If you select `Level 2Ô∏è‚É£` on the `~/Desktop` folder, here is an example of output you can have :

![level_explanation](./images/level_explanation.webp)

Optionally, you can write a regex expression to the `üö´ Reject Files` parameter. If the files matches you regex parameter, it will be excluded from the result. For example the following regex expression `^\.|^\~|desktop\.ini` will allow you to exclude common hidden and temp files.

üí° Note that if you let it empty, all files will be listed

#### Using Workflow File Filter

Invoke the first flow with the `üïπÔ∏è Trigger 1` and search for the folder or the file you want to register the filenames of and press ‚èé.

![normal_search](./images/normal_search.webp)

Alternatively, use the `Alfred Buffer` to select folder(s) and files(s) at the same time !! Basic commands are :

* ‚å•‚Üë to add a file to the buffer from Alfred's results.
* ‚å•‚Üì to add a file and move to the next item in your list of results.
* ‚å•‚Üê to remove the last item from the buffer.
* ‚å•‚Üí to action all items in the buffer.
* ‚å•‚å´ to remove all items from the buffer.

To know more on how to use `Alfred Buffer`, follow this [link](https://www.alfredapp.com/help/features/file-search/#file-buffer).

üí° Note that `Alfred Buffer` is preferred compare to the `{query}`, meaning that if you select a folder/file (by clicking on it or by pressing enter ‚èé) that is not included in the buffer, **it will not be included in the xlsx file**.

![alfred_buffer](./images/alfred_buffer.webp)

#### Using Alfred Universal Actions

Select the folder(s) / files(s) you want to grab the name of within alfred using `Quick Search` and run `Universal Actions` with ‚Üí or ‚å•‚Üí if you used the `Alfred buffer`. Select "Get filenames in a spreadsheet".

![universal_action](./images/universal_action.webp)

If you want to know more on how to use Alfred Universal Actions, follow this [link](https://www.alfredapp.com/help/features/universal-actions/).

### üíΩ Renaming files

Edit the **column D** of the xlsx generated file with new filenames and **include file extension**. Please, don't insert, delete, or edit any other columns and don't change the worksheet name `Terminal`. Don't forget to save the file with ‚åòS. You can modify the xlsx filename as your convenience [optional].

üí° Note that changing a file extension (png to jpg for example) can potentially break the file ! You can prevent this by setting the `üõ°Ô∏è Safe renaming` parameter to `True üëç`. If you still want to change the file extension (jpg to JPEG for example), set the value to `False üëé`.

Invoke the second flow with the `üïπÔ∏è Trigger 2` and select the xlsx file that should be used for the renaming operation and press ‚èé. Hold the ‚åò key and press ‚èé to reveal the file in the finder. Alternatively you can open the file in the default application by pressing ‚å•‚èé.

![rename_xlsx_selection](./images/rename_xlsx_selection.webp)

Review your parameter and launch the renaming operation by selecting `‚úÖ Rename Files` and press ‚èé.

üí° Note that if you want to change back from new names (in column D) to old names (columns B+C), you can set up the `üåä Workflow renaming direction` parameter to `Reversed üëà`. Otherwise let it to `Normal üëâ`.

![rename_params](./images/rename_params.webp)

#### Logs output

Check the logs of your compression under the `üìÇ Data folder`. The log file can contains two types of messages : 

1. If everything went well you'll have the following message : `INFO:root:‚úÖ Renaming successful: {old_file} ‚áí {new_file}`
2. If an error occurs, you'll have : `INFO:root:‚ùå Error renaming {old_file}: {error_description}`

üí° Note that renaming operation will always create a log file that is named `{name_of_the_excel_file}{log_timestamp}.log`

